    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1956-02-11T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1956-02-11T08:00:00-05:00" n="92"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d92">
                <head>92. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Egypt</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d92fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 120.1580/2–1156. Secret. Received at 2:01 a.m., February 12. Repeated
                        to Damascus, Amman, Baghdad, Beirut, Jidda, Tel Aviv, London, Paris, Ankara,
                        Tehran, Jerusalem, and <gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-02-11T15:00:00+02:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 11, 1956—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1559. Reference Embassy telegram 1554.<note n="2" xml:id="d92fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_HPT1">Hart</persName> had reported in telegram 1554
                        from Cairo, February 10, that the previous evening <persName
                            corresp="#p_FM1">Fawzi</persName> expressed “his concern over crisis
                        which would result if Israel recommenced work in D.Z. at Banat Yacub. Asking
                        that he not be quoted he stated in substance: ‘it is not that we are afraid
                        but there is no use in having a fight if we can avoid it. We are therefore
                        undertaking conversations with each Arab State to urge that further
                        consideration be given to “<persName corresp="#p_JE1">Johnston</persName>
                        plan”.’” (<hi rend="italic">Ibid.,</hi> 120.1580/2–1056)</note> British
                    Embassy reports Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_TSH1">Trevelyan</persName>
                    asked <persName corresp="#p_FM1">Fawzi</persName> February 7 whether Egypt could
                    exert its influence to persuade Arab States accept <persName corresp="#p_JE1"
                        >Johnston</persName> Plan. <persName corresp="#p_FM1">Fawzi</persName>
                    replied: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>Present time most unpropitious;</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>If Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JE1">Johnston</persName> were to
                            come to Cairo and fail obtain Arab concurrence situation would be even
                            worse than now;</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>
                            <p>Egypt intended, however, sound out chances for Arab adoption plan in
                                forthcoming conversations with Jordanians.</p>
                            <p>British Embassy very dubious chances Arab acceptance <persName
                                    corresp="#p_JE1">Johnston</persName> Plan. Their views based on: <list>
                                    <label>(a)</label>
                                    <item>Jordanian Foreign Minister’s conversation with Ambassador
                                        Duke which although less “bellicose” than that with Rifai
                                        reported Amman’s 414<note n="3" xml:id="d92fn3">
                                            <ref target="#d83">Document 83</ref>.</note> was
                                        apparently equally categoric,</item>
                                    <label>(b)</label>
                                    <item>Internal conditions in Syria,</item>
                                    <label>(c)</label>
                                    <item>Inability Egypt no matter how much it might wish avoid
                                        hostilities effectively persuade Jordan and Syrian
                                        Governments that their acceptance plan would obtain popular
                                        support in those countries.</item>
                                </list>
                            </p>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Byroade</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
